children.text: There has not been adequate clearance of at least 400mm provided under the sub-floor frame to the ground, resulting in a damp environment, which according to the BCA, encourages timber rot, fungus growth and the potential for termite activity.
Part 3.4.1.2 of the National Construction Code’s Building Code of Australia (BCA) states that
‘sub-floor spaces must have clearance between the ground surface and the underside of the lowest horizontal member in the subfloor in accordance with Table 3.4.1.1’.
Additionally, Australian Standard AS 3660.1 Termite Management states in clause 3.3.2 Access for visual inspection that
‘A minimum clearance of 400 mm between finished ground level and any structural components or other obstructions (e.g. bearers, joists, plumbing fixtures or ducting systems)’.

As the building surveyor has determined that this dwelling is in a designated termite zone, the builder will need to extend the ground clearances to a minimum of 400mm to comply with part 3.4.1.2 of the BCA.
